(this["webpackJsonppraveenoruganti-courses"]=this["webpackJsonppraveenoruganti-courses"]||[]).push([[156],{725:function(e,n,o){"use strict";o.r(n),n.default=" BOM(Browser Object Model) represents the current browser window. The main purpose of Browser Object Model is to manipulate the properties and methods which are associated with the browser window.\n\n## Window Object\n\n![screenshot of the app](https://praveenoruganti.github.io/courses/images/js/BOM.PNG)\n\nTo access the Browser Object Model(BOM) we can use the window object.\nFor example,\n\n```jsx\nwindow.document.getElementById('topbar');\ndocument.getElementById('topbar');\n\nwindow.alert('This is window');\nalert('This is without window');\n\n```\nThis window object also gives us access to some methods like\n\n- setTimeout()\n- setInterval()\n- alert()\n- confirm()\n- prompt()\n- open()\n- close()\n\nFor example,\n\n```jsx\nconfirm(\"Are you sure?\");\nprompt(\"Please enter your name\");\nopen('https://praveenoruganti.github.io');\nclose();\n```\n## Screen Object\nThe JavaScript screen object holds information of the browser screen. It can be used to display screen width, height, availableWidth, availableHeight, colorDepth, pixelDepth etc.\nFor example,\n```jsx\nconsole.log(`Window Screen Width ".concat(window.screen.width,"`);\nconsole.log(`Window Screen Available Width ").concat(window.screen.availWidth,"`);\nconsole.log(`Window Screen Height ").concat(window.screen.height,"`);\nconsole.log(`Window Screen Available Height ").concat(window.screen.availHeight,'`);\n```\n## Navigator Object\nThe navigator object contains information about the browser where your application is running.\nFor example,\n```jsx\nconsole.log(window.navigator.userAgent);\nconsole.log(navigator.onLine);\n```\n\n## History Object\nThe JavaScript history object represents an array of URLs visited by the user.\n\nit gives us two methods:\n- back()- It loads the previous page from browser history.\n- forward()- It loads the next page from browser history.\n\nFor example,\n```jsx\nwindow.history.back();\nwindow.history.forward();\n```\n\n## Location Object\nThe location object can be used to get the details of the current page address. It can also redirect the browser to a new page in same browser tab.\nFor example,\n```jsx\nconsole.log(location.href);\nconsole.log(location.hostname);\nconsole.log(location.pathname);\nconsole.log(location.search);\nlocation.assign("https://praveenoruganti.github.io");\n```\nYou can also check out the [Demo](https://praveenoruganti.github.io/courses/demo/js/BOM)\n\n ')}}]);